Let $\triangle A'HC \cong \triangle AHC$ be a reflection $\triangle AHC$ over $\overline{AC}$ and then let $\triangle B'HC \cong \triangle BHC$ be a reflection $\triangle BHC$ over $\overline{BC}$. Then since $\frac{HP}{PB} = \frac{CQ}{QB} = 1$, then $PB=HB'=HC$ and $AQ=QC'$. Therefore, using area, $$\frac{[HPB]}{[HPC]}=\frac{PB}{PC}=\frac{HB'}{BC},$$ and $$\frac{[AQB]}{[BQC]}=\frac{AQ}{QC}=\frac{HB}{B'C}.$$ But since $[HPB]+[BQC]=[BHC]=[AQB]+[HCB],$ it follows that $$\cancel{\frac{PB}{PC}}\frac{HQ}{QB}+\cancel{\frac{AQ}{QC}}\frac{HP}{PC}=\cancel{\frac{AQ}{QC}}\frac{HB}{B'C}+\cancel{\frac{PB}{PC}}\frac{HQ}{QB}\Rightarrow\frac{QB}{QC}=\frac{BH}{HC}$$ which means that $\triangle BHC \sim \triangle QBC \iff \angle BPC = \angle BHC.$ Thus, $$[AHC]=[BPQ] \text{, so \ \[PH^2-HQ^2=\frac{AH}{AC}HB \cdot \frac{HB}{HA}HC=HB^2=HB'\cdot BC\] and \ [AHQ]=\left[BHC=BPQ \implies AH(AQ-QP+PQ)= (HP^{-1}-HQ^{-1})BP\cdot HC=BP\cdot BP\] }\]} believed to hold. The equality and expression holds for general $A,H \in ABC$ as well. Hence,[asy]
